LRADAR
======

The lradar command sweeps from a radar-capable land unit and reveals
terrain in a radius around it, updating your fog-of-war map. It's the
land-unit-sourced counterpart to 'radar' (which sweeps from radar
STATION sectors — see 'info radar').

COMMAND
-------
  lradar UNIT-SPEC    Sweep from radar-capable unit(s) matching UNIT-SPEC
  lradar *            Sweep from every eligible owned unit
  lradar c            Sweep from every unit in army c (see 'info army')

UNIT-SPEC accepts a uid ("5"), a uid range ("0-5"), a comma list, "*"
for all of yours, "~" for units with no army assigned, or a single
letter naming an army.

ELIGIBILITY
-----------
  The unit's type must have radar capability (check 'show land b' or
  the unit's type description — not every land unit type can do this,
  only ones flagged for it, same idea as a plane needing bomber
  capability to bomb).
  The unit must not be stowed on a ship or another land unit.
  Efficiency and mobility do not gate whether a unit can sweep, but
  low efficiency does reduce its range (see RANGE below).

RANGE
-----
  Range is determined by your technology level, the unit's spy stat
  (a per-type constant — better radar units see farther), and the
  unit's current efficiency:

    range = floor( spy * (50 + tech) / (200 + tech) * eff / 100 )
    minimum range: 1

  This is the exact same formula 'radar' uses for sectors, just with
  the unit type's spy stat standing in for the radar sector's fixed
  power-16 constant.

  In practice this makes land radar units short-range mobile scouts,
  not a substitute for a radar station: the "radar unit" type has
  spy=3 (versus a radar sector's spy=16), so even at very high tech
  its range tops out around 3, and at low-to-mid tech it's often
  clamped to the minimum range of 1. Use it to see a little further
  than your own sector as your army advances, not to map wide areas
  — that's what a chain of radar sectors is for.

WHAT YOU SEE
------------
  Same display rules as 'radar':
  Within range/3 of the unit:    actual sector mnemonic
  Beyond range/3 (outer ring):   '?' (something is there)
  Own sectors, sea (~), mountains (^), wasteland (+):
                                  always show actual mnemonic

  The center (the unit's own sector) is marked '0' on the display.

FOG OF WAR
----------
  Same fog-of-war rules as 'radar' — this sweep updates your bmap
  for the area scanned, same as a sector-based sweep would.

EXAMPLES
--------
  lradar *          Sweep from every eligible owned unit.
  lradar 5          Sweep from unit 5 only.
  lradar c          Sweep from every unit in army c.

KNOWN GAPS (v1)
----------------
  4.4.1's real lradar command also accepts a sector-spec, letting it
  sweep from radar STATION sectors too (redundant with 'radar', which
  already covers that case) — not ported here, to keep the two
  commands' roles distinct: 'radar' for sector-sourced sweeps,
  'lradar' for unit-sourced ones.

